land, United Kingdom":"Otterden, Kent, Anglie, United Kingdom","St. Lawrence the Martyr Churchyard, Otterden, Kent, England":"Otterden, Kent, Anglie, United Kingdom","Otterden, Kent, England":"Otterden, Kent, Anglie"},"da":{"–1488":"–1488","1455–1502":"1455–1502","1470–1509":"1470–1509","1472–Female":"1472–Afdød","1475–Female":"1475–Afdød","1477–Male":"1477–Afdød","–Male":"Afdød","1502":"1502","1488":"1488","1477":"1477","1455":"1455","1475":"1475","about 1477":"omkring 1477","1472":"1472","about 1475":"omkring 1475","1509":"1509","1470":"1470","1382":"1382","about 1472":"omkring 1472","of England":"England","Otterden, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Otterden, Kent, England, United Kingdom","St. Lawrence the Martyr Churchyard, Otterden, Kent, England":"Otterden, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Otterden, Kent, England":"Otterden, Kent, England"},"nl":{"–1488":"–1488","1455–1502":"1455–1502","1470–1509":"1470–1509","1472–Female":"1472–Overleden","1475–Female":"1475–Overleden","1477–Male":"1477–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1502":"1502","1488":"1488","1477":"1477","1455":"1455","1475":"1475","about 1477":"circa 1477","1472":"1472","about 1475":"circa 1475","1509":"1509","1470":"1470","1382":"1382","about 1472":"circa 1472","of England":"England","Otterden, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Otterden, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","St. Lawrence the Martyr Churchyard, Otterden, Kent, England":"Otterden, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Otterden, Kent, England":"Otterden, Kent, England"},"en":{"–1488":"–1488","1455–1502":"1455–1502","1470–1509":"1470–1509","1472–Female":"1472–Deceased","1475–Female":"1475–Deceased","1477–Male":"1477–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1502":"1502","1488":"1488","1477":"1477","1455":"1455","1475":"1475","about 1477":"about 1477","1472":"1472","about 1475":"about 1475","1509":"1509","1470":"1470","1382":"1382","about 1472":"about 1472","of England":"England","Otterden, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Otterden, Kent, England, United Kingdom","St. Lawrence the Martyr Churchyard, Otterden, Kent, England":"Otterden, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Otterden, Kent, England":"Otterden, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Church","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: topographic name mostly found in southern and midland England, for someone who lived near a church, or possibly an occupational name for someone who worked at a church, such as a verger or sexton, from Middle English <i>chirche</i> ‘church’. The word comes from Old English <i>cyrice</i>, ultimately from medieval Greek <i>kyrikon</i>, for earlier <i>kyriakōn (dōma)</i> ‘(house) of the Lord’, from <i>kyrios</i> ‘lord’. Compare   Kirk  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of German   Kirch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Kirk","meanings":["Scottish, English, and Danish: from Middle English, Danish <i>kirk</i> ‘church’ (Old Norse <i>kirkja</i>), a topographic name for someone who lived near a church. This name has also been established in Ireland since the 16th century or earlier."]},{"name":"Kern","meanings":["German, Dutch, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from Middle High German <i>kerne</i> ‘kernel, seed, pip’; Middle Dutch <i>kern(e)</i>, <i>keerne</i>; German <i>Kern</i> or Yiddish <i>kern</i> ‘grain’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a farmer, or a nickname for a physically small person. As a Jewish surname, it is mainly artificial.","English (southeastern): metonymic occupational name for a maker or user of milk churns, from Middle English <i>kern</i>, <i>kirn</i>, <i>kurn</i>, a side-form of <i>chern</i> ‘churn’. Compare   Church  .","Slovenian: nickname for a stunted person, from an old spelling of <i>krn</i> ‘stunted’."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":12,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":85,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Alice Church was born as the daug